fullstack --> frontend +backend



frontend
________

Frontend is a visual and intereactive layer of a website or application that users directly
see and intereact with through a webserver or mobile app.

it is also called the client side because it runs on the users
device(browser/mobile)


Reaposibilities of frontend
_______________ __ ________

1. Display web pages and user interface(UI)2.
2. accepts userinput(forms,buttons,search boxes)
3. validates user input before sending it to the server.
4. calls backend API to fetch or send data .
5. display the response received from baackend.
6. provides animations and interactive effects.
   by preparing frontend layer we are using some tech like html,css,js.bootstrap.

Bakend
______

backend is a server side part of an application .
users cannot see it directly , but it performs all the business logic,security,data processing,and database operators.

it acts as the brain of the application.

Responsibilities of Backend
________________ __ _______

1. process clients request .
2. implements business logic.
3. connects with database.
4. performs crud operations.
5. authenticates and authorise users.
6. encrypts passwords and authorize users.
7. generate reports.
8. returns responses to the frontend.
9. we have to some languages to build backend java,.net,php,c,++.


API ( Application programming interface)
___ _____________________________________

API is a set of the rules and protocols that allows two different applications or systems
 to communicate and exchange dta with out exposing their internaal implementation.

it acts as bridge between the frontend and backend between two different software systems.


Advantages of API's
__________ __ ___ _ 

1. enables communication between different systems.
2. promotes code reuseability.
3. platform independent.
4. faster application development.
5. supports integration with third-party-services.
6. improves scalability.
7. easy to maintain.


Storage Areas
_______ _____

as a part of our applications we required to store data like customer info,billing info, calls info, ..etc. 
to store these data we require some storage areas.

there are two types of storage areas such as 
1. Temporary Storage
_ __________ _______

these are the memory areas where the data will be stored temporarily.
examples : all JVM memory areas (like heap,stack,methodarea,pc registers,native method stack).
           once JVM is shutdown all these memory areas will be cleared automatically.

2. Permanent Storage Area
_ __________ _______ ____

it is also known as persistent storage areas. where data will be stored permanently .
examples: Filesystems,Databases,Data warehouses...etc

File Management Systems(FMS)
____ __________ ____________

a file management system is a system where data is stored in files on the operatimng systems.
each application program must handle its own storage data. retriva and updating . File systems can be provided by the 
local operating systems.
files systems are best suitable to store very less amount of information.
examples: a library management system storing books ina separate text files like books.txt,members.txt...ect.

LImitations of file management systems
____________ __ ____ ________ ________

1. data redundancy - same data is stored in multiple files.
2. data redundancy - uodates in one file may not be reflected in another .
3. poor data security - no proper accessed control.
4. difficult data retrieval - searching customs programs.
5. intergrity issues - no constraints(ex : roll number uniqueness)
6. scalability issues - hard to manage as data grows.

to overcome the above problems in file systems we should go for databses

Database Management System (DBMS)
________ __________ ______
a DBMs is a collection programmes that enables users to create,manage,and manipulate databases.
it acts as an interface between user and databases.

Advantages
__________
1. we can store huge amount of information in databse.
2. query language support is available for every databses and hence we perform database operators
   easily.
3. to access data present in the databse. compulsory username and password must be required hence data is 
    secured.
4. inside databade data will be stored in form of tables. while developing database table schemas , databse
   admin follows various normalization techniques and we can implement various constraints like unique ker , primary key
   , forien key,...ect. which prevent data duplication . hence there is no chance off data inconsistaency problems.

Limitations of databases
___________ __ _________

1. Databases cannot be stored huge amount of information like(terabytes).
2. databases can be provide supports for only structured data (tabular data or relational data).
and cannot provide supports for unstructured data or semi-structured data(likes,videos,audios,xml data).

to overcome these problems we should go for some more advanced databases like data warehouses, big sata....etc.

